\begin_layout Itemize
Initial condition 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho(t=0)=\rho^{0}(v)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Adapt (unnecessary) assumption that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1}{h}=N
\]

\end_inset

is an integer 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Compartmentalize the density 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho(v,t)=\sum_{k=1}^{N}\rho_{k}(v,t)
\]

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{k}=0$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $v\notin[(k-1)h,kh]$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Initial data 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho^{0}(v)=\sum_{k=1}^{N}\rho_{k}^{0}(v)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Write 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial}{\partial\tau}\rho=\rho(v-h)-\rho(v)+A[\rho]\delta(v)
\]

\end_inset

as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d}{d\tau}\rho_{n}=\rho_{n-1}-\rho_{n}+A[\rho_{N}]\delta(v)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{n}(\tau=0)=\rho_{n}^{0}(v)$
\end_inset

 is smooth.
 After the first instant a delta function appears at the origin, since the
 density evolves by incremental jumps of 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
After the first instant delta functions appear at all multiples of 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This suggest the decomposition 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho_{k}(v,t)=\hat{\rho}_{k}(v,\tau)+D_{k}(\tau)\delta(v-(k-1))d
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\rho}_{k}(v,t)$
\end_inset

 is smooth and 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{k}(\tau)$
\end_inset

 represents the strength of the delta function in the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

th interval 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Initially 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
D_{k}(0)=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For the first compartment, we obtain 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d}{d\tau}D_{1}=\underbrace{-D_{1}}_{\text{leaves}}+\underbrace{A}_{\text{enters}}=-D_{1}+D_{N}+\int_{1-h}^{1}\rho_{N}(w)dw
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This notation is strange, because 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{d}{d\tau}$
\end_inset

 refers to one time unit in which one spike arrives? What if more spikes
 arrive? We need to make the time step small enough to ensure that this
 does not happen
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d}{d\tau}\hat{\rho}_{1}=-\hat{\rho}_{1}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In the second interval we obtain 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d}{d\tau}D_{2}=\underbrace{D_{1}}_{\text{enters}}-\underbrace{D_{2}}_{\text{leaves}}
\]

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d}{d\tau}\hat{p}_{2}=T_{h}\hat{\rho}_{1}-\hat{\rho}_{2}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The reset mechanism introduces the delta distributions which are not real.
 How could we get around this?
\end_layout

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T_{h}f(v)=f(v-h)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
These steps carry over to an arbitrary interval, and if we define 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boldsymbol{L}=\begin{pmatrix}-1 & 0 &  &  & 0\\
T_{h} & -1\\
0 & \ddots & \ddots\\
 &  &  &  & 0\\
0 &  & 0 & T_{h} & -1
\end{pmatrix}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The smooth part 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{\boldsymbol{\rho}}=[\hat{\rho}_{1},\ldots,\hat{\rho}_{N}]
\]

\end_inset

satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d}{d\tau}\hat{\boldsymbol{\rho}}=L\hat{\boldsymbol{\rho}}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Proof 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d}{d\tau}\hat{p}_{k}=T_{h}\hat{\rho}_{k-1}-\hat{\rho}_{k}
\]

\end_inset

what we want to have.
 Multiplying 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boldsymbol{L}\hat{\boldsymbol{\rho}}=\begin{pmatrix}-1 & 0 &  &  & 0\\
T_{h} & -1\\
0 & \ddots & \ddots\\
 &  &  &  & 0\\
0 &  & 0 & T_{h} & -1
\end{pmatrix}\begin{pmatrix}\rho_{1}\\
\rho_{2}\\
\vdots\\
\\
\rho_{N}
\end{pmatrix}=\begin{pmatrix}-\hat{\rho}_{1}\\
T_{h}\hat{\rho}_{1}-\hat{\rho}_{2}\\
\vdots\\
\\
T_{h}\hat{\rho}_{N-1}-\hat{\rho}_{N}
\end{pmatrix}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Note that the smooth part will eventually vanish because mass get only moves
 by discrete jumps 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The translation operator commutes with the time derivative 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The solution is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{\boldsymbol{\rho}}=e^{\tau\boldsymbol{L}}\boldsymbol{\rho}^{0}
\]

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e^{\tau\boldsymbol{L}}=e^{-\tau}e^{L}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e^{\tau\boldsymbol{L}}=e^{-\tau}\begin{pmatrix}1 & 0 &  &  & 0\\
T_{h} & 1\\
\frac{T_{h}^{2}}{2}! & \ddots & \ddots\\
 &  &  &  & 0\\
\frac{T_{h}^{N-1}}{(N-1)!} &  & \frac{T_{h}^{2}}{2!} & T_{h} & 1
\end{pmatrix}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Proof 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
How can we calculate a matrix exponential? Brute force 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e^{\tau\boldsymbol{L}}=I+\tau\boldsymbol{L}+\frac{1}{2!}(\tau\boldsymbol{L})^{2}+\frac{1}{3!}(\tau\boldsymbol{L}){}^{3}+\ldots
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We can write 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{L}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boldsymbol{L}=\begin{pmatrix}-1 & 0 &  &  & 0\\
T_{h} & -1\\
0 & \ddots & \ddots\\
 &  &  &  & 0\\
0 &  & 0 & T_{h} & -1
\end{pmatrix}=\boldsymbol{A}-\boldsymbol{I}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boldsymbol{A}=\begin{pmatrix}0 & 0 &  &  & 0\\
T_{h} & 0\\
0 & \ddots & \ddots\\
 &  &  &  & 0\\
0 &  & 0 & T_{h} & 0
\end{pmatrix}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{I}$
\end_inset

 commutes with 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{A}$
\end_inset

, we can write 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e^{\boldsymbol{L}\tau}=e^{\boldsymbol{A}\tau}e^{-\boldsymbol{I}\tau}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e^{-\boldsymbol{I}\tau}=e^{-\tau}\boldsymbol{I}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Do calculate the matrix exponential 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e^{\boldsymbol{A}\tau}
\]

\end_inset

we Taylor expand 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
e^{\boldsymbol{A}\tau} & =\boldsymbol{I}+\boldsymbol{A}\tau+\frac{1}{2!}(\boldsymbol{A}\tau)^{2}+\ldots\\
 & =\begin{pmatrix}1 & 0 &  &  & 0\\
T_{h}\tau & 1\\
\frac{(\tau T_{h})^{2}}{2}! & \ddots & \ddots\\
 &  &  &  & 0\\
\frac{(\tau T_{h})^{N-1}}{(N-1)!} &  & \frac{(\tau T_{h})^{2}}{2!} & \tau T_{h} & 1
\end{pmatrix}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We arrive at 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
e^{\boldsymbol{L}\tau} & =e^{\boldsymbol{A}\tau}e^{-\boldsymbol{I}\tau}\\
 & =e^{-\tau}\boldsymbol{I}\begin{pmatrix}1 & 0 &  &  & 0\\
T_{h}\tau & 1\\
\frac{(\tau T_{h})^{2}}{2}! & \ddots & \ddots\\
 &  &  &  & 0\\
\frac{(\tau T_{h})^{N-1}}{(N-1)!} &  & \frac{(\tau T_{h})^{2}}{2!} & \tau T_{h} & 1
\end{pmatrix}\\
 & =e^{-\tau}\begin{pmatrix}1 & 0 &  &  & 0\\
T_{h}\tau & 1\\
\frac{(\tau T_{h})^{2}}{2}! & \ddots & \ddots\\
